<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8" /><title>Introduction to Arrays</title><style type="text/css">body {	font-family: courier, monospace;	color:#FF6633;	}	.instructions {	color: #666666;	font-family: georgia, serif;	}	code {	color: #444;	font-weight: bold;	font-size: 1.1em;}</style></head><body><header><h1 class="instructions">Introduction to Arrays</h1></header><article><h2 class="instructions">About Arrays</h2><p class="instructions">Arrays are just variables that hold multiple values simultaneously. There are indexed and associative arrays. You can create an array by repeating the name of the array variable for each array element, or you can use the <code>array()</code> function. After you create each array, use the <code>var_dump()</code> function to print the contents of your array to the page (hint:put in the preformatted text tag for more readable output!)</p><h3 class="instructions">Processed Meat (indexed array)</h3><p class="instructions">Write an indexed array called <code>$processed_meat</code> with the following array elements: bacon, sausage, spam, bologna. Do NOT use the array() function. Try to print the value of your array to the page using <code>echo</code>. What happens?</p><!-- write your first script here; remember to use var_dump() to view the contents of the array! --><?php$processed_meat[0] = 'bacon';$processed_meat[1] = 'sausage';$processed_meat[2] = 'spam';$processed_meat[3] = 'bologna';echo $processed_meat;echo '<pre>'.var_dump($processed_meat).'</pre>';?><h3 class="instructions">Game (indexed array)</h3><p class="instructions">Write an indexed array called <code>$game</code> with the following array elements: venison, quail, elk. This time, use the <code>array()</code> function and use <code>print_r()</code> to view your array's contents.</p><!-- write your second script here; remember to use print_r() to view the contents of the array! --><?php$game = array('venison', 'quail', 'elk');echo '<pre>';print_r($game);echo '</pre>';?><h3 class="instructions">Fancy Menu (associative array)</h3><p class="instructions">Write an associative array called $fancy_menu. The keys are: starter, soup, main, dessert. The values are: escargot, minestrone, short ribs, New York cheesecake. Don't use the array function. View the contents using <code>var_dump()</code>.</p><!-- write your third script here; remember to use var_dump() to view the contents of the array!  --><?php$fancy_meat['starter'] = 'escargot';$fancy_meat['soup'] = 'minestrone';$fancy_meat['main'] = 'short ribs';$fancy_meat['dessert'] = 'New Your cheesecake';echo '<pre>';var_dump($fancy_meat);echo '</pre>';?><h3 class="instructions">Plain Menu (associative array)</h3><p class="instructions">Write an associative array called <code>$plain_menu</code>. The keys are: snack, dinner, drink, treat. The values are: nachos, fish sticks, Hawai'ian Punch, brownie. Use the array function. View the contents using<code>print_r()</code></p><!-- write your fourth script here; remember to use print_r() to view the contents of the array!  --><?php$plain_menu = array (	'snack' => 'nachos',	'dinner' => 'fish sticks',	'drink' => 'Hawai\'ian Punch',	'treat' => 'brownie');echo '<pre>';print_r($plain_menu);echo '</pre>';?></pre><h3 class="instructions">Outputting array elements</h3><p class="instructions">Write a script that outputs one array element for each array as follows. For $processed_meat, print the third array element. For <code>$game</code>, print the first array element. For <code>$fancy_menu</code>, print the second array element. For <code>$plain_menu</code>, print the last array element. Be sure you have line breaks between each script's output. Remember the ways you can do that?</p><!-- Write your scripts here. --><?phpecho $processed_meat[2].'<br />';echo $game[0].'<br />';echo $fancy_meat['soup'].'<br />';echo $plain_menu['treat'];?></article></body></html>